Furthermore, a comparison of the percentage removal values for different dyes using metal oxide-based green carbon dots with those reported in the literature (Table 2
                           ) shows that the degradation efficiency achieved in this study is significantly higher than previously reported values [27–31,32–36]. The data collectively demonstrate the efficacy of various nanohybrids derived from organic waste sources in removing pollutants through photocatalysis and sonocatalysis. The removal efficiencies of these nanohybrids, ranging from 93.49 % to 99 %, underscore their potential as sustainable and environmentally friendly solutions for wastewater treatment. A novel, low-cost method was developed to synthesize C-dots from Crocus cancellatus
                           , which were then used to prepare a carbon dot based magnetic nanocomposite CDs@Fe3O4. The nanocomposite exhibited exceptional photocatalytic activity, removing 94.4 % of fluorescein dye within 60 min under sunlight. The nanocomposite retained strong photocatalytic activity even after five recycles, removing 75 % of the dye [32]. In the study reported by Ghasemi and coworkers, N-doped ZnO/fulvic acid/carbon dot composite were fabricated using hydrothermal approach for sonocatalytic degradation of methylene blue dye [27]. The C-dots were synthesized from dried saffron plant. The result demonstrated 94 % degradation of methylene blue dye in 50 min of irradiation time by adopting synergetic capability of ultrasonic irradiation and N-ZnO/FA/C-dots. While in our study 99 % of dye was removed in 10 min of contact time which clearly depicts the potential of CeO2@ C-dots green nanocomposites as effective solutions for dye removal from wastewater. Also, the carbon dot based materials showed good scope of reusability and biodegradability emphasizing utilization of the biowaste materials as synthesis materials or precursors.
